{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2cc15a5c-10df-4fd3-8bf6-3c719de05e06","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n}\n```\n\n**Why modernize:**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor could throw instead of `CreateUser`)\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` pinpoints the exact call and lets you inspect the exception (message, `ParamName`, inner exception, etc.)\n- The test fails clearly if no exception is thrown","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6b8ccc59-897d-435f-b841-c50cb6fa8a7e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":261,"requestId":"702B:362770:B6807A:D41090:69F2AF5A"},"id":"0f052a8b-3431-4e62-854c-6e84da83cba9","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:24:48.105Z","parentId":"a2bbfb69-b9d6-4db7-a60d-27c022571c5b"}
